  <p>Every year as Melbourne heads into autumn, thousands of homeowners light their first fire of the season without giving the chimney a second thought. Sometimes that's fine. Sometimes it isn't. Here's the honest assessment of the risk — and what it actually depends on.</p>

  <h2>The Short Answer: It Depends on When It Was Last Cleaned</h2>

  <p>If your chimney was professionally cleaned at the end of last winter, you've used it normally with good quality dry hardwood, and it's been drawing well — a single fire without an immediate clean is unlikely to cause a problem. The risk is low, not zero, but low.</p>

  <p>If your chimney hasn't been cleaned in two or more years, has never been professionally cleaned, has an unknown service history, or if you've noticed any change in how it draws — the honest answer is no, it's not safe to use without getting it inspected first. The risk of a chimney fire from accumulated creosote is real, and chimney fires can and do spread to the structure of the house.</p>

  <h2>What Actually Makes It Unsafe</h2>

  <h3>Creosote Buildup</h3>
  <p>Every time you burn wood, combustion byproducts travel up the flue. Some of that condenses on the cooler flue walls as creosote — a flammable residue that accumulates with every fire. In its early stages it's a dry, powdery soot. Over time it develops into a harder, tar-like coating. Advanced creosote — sometimes called stage 3 or glazed creosote — is extremely difficult to remove and highly flammable.</p>

  <p>A creosote fire inside the flue burns at temperatures exceeding 1000°C. That's enough to crack flue liners, ignite nearby timber framing, and in the worst cases, spread to the roof. It doesn't take years of neglect to reach dangerous levels — particularly if you've been burning unseasoned wood or softwoods like pine.</p>

  <h3>Blockages</h3>
  <p>A chimney that sits unused through Melbourne's spring and summer is an attractive nesting site for birds — particularly starlings and sparrows. A nest built in the flue over summer can completely block airflow. Lighting a fire with a blocked flue forces smoke back into the room and can ignite the nest material, causing a chimney fire from the top down.</p>

  <p>Debris — leaf litter, bark, crumbled mortar — can also partially block the flue without you knowing it until the fire behaves strangely.</p>

  <h3>Structural Deterioration</h3>
  <p>Old or unmaintained chimneys — particularly the original brick chimneys common in Melbourne's Victorian and Edwardian period homes — can develop cracks in the flue lining over time. A cracked flue liner can allow heat and combustion gases, including carbon monoxide, to escape into the wall cavity or living space. This isn't visible from below without a proper inspection.</p>

  <div class="callout">
    <p>Carbon monoxide is colourless and odourless. If your chimney has structural damage and you're burning without adequate ventilation, CO exposure is a genuine risk — not a theoretical one.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>The Situations Where You Should Not Light a Fire</h2>

  <p>Be cautious and get a professional inspection before using your fireplace if any of these apply:</p>

  <p><strong>Unknown service history</strong> — you've moved into a property with a fireplace and don't know when it was last cleaned. This is the single most common situation where problems occur.</p>

  <p><strong>More than 12 months since last clean</strong> — particularly if you used it regularly through last winter.</p>

  <p><strong>The chimney has been unused for several years</strong> — long periods of non-use increase the likelihood of nest blockages, deteriorated mortar, and moisture damage.</p>

  <p><strong>You've noticed a change in draw</strong> — if the fire used to perform well and now draws sluggishly or smoke comes back into the room, something has changed and it needs investigating before you continue using it.</p>

  <p><strong>You can see or smell heavy creosote</strong> — oily black deposits around the firebox, or a strong acrid smell from the flue, indicate significant buildup.</p>

