  <h2>What About "Just One Fire to Test It"?</h2>

  <p>This is the most common rationalisation — lighting a small fire first to see how the chimney performs, on the assumption that any problem will become obvious before it gets serious. The issue with this logic is that a chimney fire can start from a single fire if creosote buildup is at the right level and temperature. The fire doesn't have to be large. You don't get a warning.</p>

  <p>A chimney fire also isn't always dramatic. Many occur without the homeowner knowing — a rumbling sound, more heat than usual from the flue, and a strong smell are common signs, but not always noticed in the moment. The damage to the flue lining is discovered later, sometimes when the next professional clean reveals cracked tiles or collapsed sections.</p>

  <h2>How Much Does an Inspection Actually Cost?</h2>

  <p>A professional chimney clean and inspection covers the full flue from firebox to pot — creosote removal, blockage check, condition report. It's not a separate charge on top of the clean. The clean and the inspection happen in the same visit.</p>

  <p>For a flue or wood heater system that's $199. For a masonry or brick chimney fireplace it's $299. Against the cost of a chimney fire — insurance excesses, structural repairs, temporary accommodation while repairs are done — it's not a difficult decision.</p>

  <h2>The Bottom Line</h2>

  <p>If you genuinely don't know when your chimney was last cleaned, or if it's been over 12 months, get it done before you use it this winter. It's not about being overly cautious — it's about understanding that creosote fires are real, they happen in Melbourne homes every year, and a 90-minute professional clean is all that stands between a safe heating season and a genuinely dangerous one.</p>
